<doc id="87121" wikidata="Q2580125" url="?curid=87121" title="Hildr">
<text>In Norse mythology, Hildr (Old Norse &quot;battle&quot;) is a valkyrie. Hildr is attested in the &quot;Prose Edda&quot; as Högni&#x27;s daughter and Hedin&#x27;s wife in the &quot;Hjaðningavíg&quot;. She had the power to revive the dead in battlefields and used it to maintain the everlasting battle between Hedin and Högni.

Hildr is also mentioned along with other valkyries in &quot;Völuspá&quot;, &quot;Darraðarljóð&quot; and other Old Norse poems. The Old Norse word &quot;hildr&quot; is a common noun meaning &quot;battle&quot; and it is not always clear when the poets had the valkyrie in mind, as a personification of battle.

== Citations ==
== General and cited references ==
